TELEGRAM HEARTBEAT — topic {{THREAD_ID}}, chat {{CHAT_ID}}, inbox {{INBOX}}, cwd {{CWD}}.
Session dir: /tmp/claude-telegram/sessions/{{THREAD_ID}}  (call it SESS below).
Bridge dir: ~/.telegram-bridge.

You are a "dumb session" in the smart-router / dumb-session model: the router
daemon owns all timing. It PUSHES you a wake nudge the moment a message arrives
(via tmux send-keys), and it computes your context gauge itself (you no longer
write SESS/status.json). This cron is ONLY a slow FALLBACK HEARTBEAT for the rare
case a wake nudge was missed (pane died, non-tmux session, send-keys race). It is
also the canonical definition of your DRAIN procedure — the wake nudge just tells
you to "run section A", so keep this in context.

There is NO backoff ladder, no idle.count, no poll.level, no per-tick rescheduling.
This heartbeat fires on one fixed slow interval. Do exactly the steps below, then
go idle.

A. DRAIN INBOX (run on every heartbeat AND whenever a wake nudge says "drain"):
   1. Take a non-blocking per-topic lock so a wake-driven drain and this heartbeat
      (or a compaction cutover) can't double-reply. Atomic mkdir lock (flock is
      NOT on macOS, do not use it):
        mkdir SESS/poll.lock.d 2>/dev/null || (another drain/cutover active -> stop)
      Hold it for steps 2-4; ALWAYS rmdir it when done (even on no messages).
   2. Read read-offset from SESS/read.offset (default 0). Read {{INBOX}}; take the
      lines AFTER it. DRAINED = number of new lines (0 if none).
   3. For each new message line (JSON: text, message_id, optional image_path):
      a. image_path present -> Read that file first (screenshot/photo); text is the caption/instruction.
      b. else treat text as a task/question for THIS session.
      c. Process with full context, tools, memory.
      d. Reply: ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-send.sh {{CHAT_ID}} {{THREAD_ID}} "<your response>"
      e. BRIDGE COMMANDS — first token is one of these RESERVED names, leading "/"
         (preferred) or "!" (legacy), case-insensitive; strip the prefix first:
           /status  -> reply with cwd + message count processed
           /context -> reply with the live context gauge: read SESS/status.json (the
                       ROUTER writes it now) and report pct, tokens, window, msgs
           /compact -> run COMPACTION HANDOFF (below) right now
           /dir <name|path> -> resolve against ~/.telegram-bridge/dir-aliases.json
                       (case-insensitive); else literal path (~ expanded). Note the change.
           /dirs    -> reply with the alias names from ~/.telegram-bridge/dir-aliases.json
           /end     -> FIRST preserve the session's work: invoke /track (journal it),
                       then /context-save (checkpoint so a future launch can resume).
                       THEN deregister: rm the registry file, closeForumTopic, delete
                       this heartbeat cron (id in SESS/poll.cron.id), reply "Session
                       detached (work tracked + checkpoint saved)."
         Only those SIX are bridge commands. Any OTHER "/" text (/track, /ship,
         /review, ...) is NOT a bridge command — treat it as a task so skills can be
         driven from the phone. (Daemon-level /new, /whoami, /sessions, /help never
         reach the inbox.)
   4. Write the new line count to SESS/read.offset. Release the lock: rmdir SESS/poll.lock.d.
   5. If DRAINED > 0, report briefly (e.g. "telegram: replied to 1 message").

B. COMPACTION — the ROUTER detects the context trigger, not you. When it sees your
   gauge cross trigger_pct it delivers a reserved `/compact` (drained in A.3.e
   above, or as a direct wake nudge). You do NOT self-check pct. Run COMPACTION
   HANDOFF below whenever you receive /compact. (Claude Code's native auto-compact
   remains the ultimate backstop if the router's detection is ever down.)

There is no section C/D — backoff and the status gauge moved to the router.

COMPACTION HANDOFF (run from the /compact command):
   You cannot shrink your own live context, so roll over to a FRESH replacement that
   restores saved state into the SAME topic. Steps, in order:
   1. Post: ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-send.sh {{CHAT_ID}} {{THREAD_ID}} "♻️ compacting — saving context and spawning a fresh session…"
   2. Invoke /context-save (or your configured save mechanism). It prints the saved
      file path; capture it, then copy to a stable handoff path:
        cp "<saved file path>" SESS/context-restore.md
   3. touch SESS/compacting.lock ; rm -f SESS/handoff-ready
   4. Spawn the replacement (attach mode). Attach intent is passed via FLAGS, not
      env vars, so it can't be inherited by a later manual spawn and hijack a topic:
        bash ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-spawn.sh \
          --attach {{THREAD_ID}} --restore SESS/context-restore.md "{{CWD}}"
   5. Wait for SESS/handoff-ready to appear (the replacement writes it after restoring
      + attaching). Poll every few seconds up to ~5 min.
        - Not appearing in time: post "⚠️ compaction replacement didn't report ready;
          staying live.", rm SESS/compacting.lock, and ABORT (keep running normally).
   6. Hand off: CronDelete THIS session's heartbeat cron (id in SESS/poll.cron.id),
      then rm SESS/compacting.lock (this releases the replacement to start its heartbeat).
   7. Post: ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-send.sh {{CHAT_ID}} {{THREAD_ID}} "✅ compacted — fresh session is live."
   8. Retire this tmux window for cleanup — ONLY if this session was spawned by the
      bridge (env TELEGRAM_BRIDGE_SPAWNED=1) AND $TMUX_PANE is set. Otherwise SKIP.
      Target the window explicitly via $TMUX_PANE (a bare rename/display resolves to
      the ACTIVE window, not this one). Read kill_old from ~/.telegram-bridge/compaction.json:
        - kill_old false (default): tmux rename-window -t "$TMUX_PANE" "DEAD - $(tmux display-message -t "$TMUX_PANE" -p '#W')"
        - kill_old true:            tmux kill-window -t "$TMUX_PANE"
   9. STOP. This session has handed off; take no further action.
